article.description: Cappie Pondexter had 17 of her 21 points in the second half and Rutgers (No. 8 ESPN/USA Today, No. 7 AP) used its pressure defense to force 26 turnovers in a tougher than expected 69-61 victory over Syracuse.
article.headline: Orange lose 13th straight game to ranked opponent
article.linkText: Rutgers uses 26 turnovers to beat Syracuse
article.story:
PISCATAWAY, N.J. (AP) -- With the Big East Conference tournament about a month away, Rutgers coach C. Vivian Stringer conducted an experiment Sunday and started her four freshmen for the first time.

Her decision made the Scarlet Knights (No. 8 ESPN/USA Today, No. 7 AP) work a lot harder than expected in posting a 69-61 victory against Syracuse, and it also may have exposed a decline in Rutgers' confidence following an embarrassing loss to No. 11 Connecticut last week.

"I don't think they are as confident," said Stringer, whose team was riding high in late December and early January after knocking off three Top 10 teams, including No. 1 LSU.

"I'll tell you the truth. I'm just being dead honest," Stringer said. "Honestly, this should not have been a contest. I don't care what I did. We should know what we need to do and be able to do it. This might speak to how fragile everything is."

Syracuse (11-10, 3-7) trailed by only a point at halftime and Rutgers wasn't able to put it away until senior Cappie Pondexter started hitting shots and the Scarlet Knights' pressure defense started forcing turnovers (26) and getting easy layups.

Pondexter had 17 of her 21 points in the second half, along with four of her five assists and five steals, in helping Rutgers (16-5, 7-2) remain unbeaten at home in 10 games.

"We didn't jump on them from the beginning," said Rutgers center Michelle Campbell, who had 18 points. "We should have jumped on them a lot more. It's all right. We won the game, but we know we have things to work on next time around."

Freshmen Matee Ajavon and Essence Carson added nine points each and Rutgers won for the 11th time in 14 games. Fellow freshman Tudy Reed and Katie Adams did not score.

Jessica Richter had 17 points for Syracuse (11-10, 3-7), which lost its 13th straight game to a ranked opponent. Vaida Sipaviciute added 13 and Chineze Nwagbo had 11 for the Orange, who are now 0-14 at the Rutgers Athletic Center.

"For where our program is now, I thought this was a great effort for our team," said Syracuse coach Keith Cieplicki, who picked up a late technical foul. "I am very proud of them. We are really learning how to compete for 40 minutes against the best teams in the country, and obviously Rutgers showed it is one of
those teams."

Syracuse made Rutgers work for this one, using its size advantage inside with Sipaviciute and Nwagbo to take a 19-14 lead.

However, the game changed when Nwagbo picked up her third foul late in the first half and her fourth in the opening minute of the second half.

A late 6-0 run that featured four points by Campbell gave the Scarlet Knights a 20-19 halftime edge. They seemingly took control with an 18-7 spurt early in the second half after Nwagbo went to the bench.

Pondexter had six points and three steals in the spurt that gave Rutgers a 39-28 lead.

Rochelle Coleman, Sipaviciute and Nwagbo then combined to score all the points in a 17-9 run that got the Orange to 48-45 on a 3-pointer by Coleman with 7:19 to play.

Pondexter then scored five points in a 7-0 spurt to push the lead to 10 points. Syracuse never got closer than seven the rest of the way.

"I still feel that if we don't turn the ball over, it's not a layup drill," Cieplicki said. "They are going to make open layups."

Syracuse shot 50 percent from the field, including 16-of-24 in the second half.
